comments.body:
Currently, we call File.Exists() and Directory.Exists() to see if path is directory or file, AND if path exists.

Yes, we could do something like:

FileAttributes fa = new File.GetAttributes(path);
if (fa & FileAttributes.Directory == FileAttributes.Directory)
{
     // is directory
}
else
{
    // is not directory
}

But above code doesn't answer the question of whether the file/directory exists.  To do so, we would need to either:
1.  Put try/catch around File.GetAttributes(), as this call will throw if path does not exist.
2.  Do something like:

FileInfo fi = new File.FileInfo(path);
if (fi.Exists)
{
   // it's a file
}

DirectoryInfo di = new Directory.DirectoryInfo(path);
if (di.Exists)
{
  // it's a directory
}
else
{
   // it doesn't exist
}

I'm not sure if either solution is better or faster than current implementation of using File.Exists() and Directory.Exists().
